column1: 92030;instagram;2019-01-03 10:36:30;FALSE;"former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel
column2: but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

column1: in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23
column2: flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia
column3: and kushner spoke with kim darroch
column4: the british ambassador to the united states
column5: according to diplomats familiar with the conversations
column6: who spoke on condition of anonymity.

column1: the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump
column2: who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric
column3: took office on jan. 20. it failed
column4: with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

column1: the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move
column2: egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution
column3: prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

column1: a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a ""high level"" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.
according to court documents made public on friday
column2: a member of trump's presidential transition team
column3: later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner
column4: told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments
column6: to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

column1: flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day

column1: 92033;instagram;2019-01-03 10:38:29;FALSE;"former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel
column2: but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

column1: in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23
column2: flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia
column3: and kushner spoke with kim darroch
column4: the british ambassador to the united states
column5: according to diplomats familiar with the conversations
column6: who spoke on condition of anonymity.

column1: the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump
column2: who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric
column3: took office on jan. 20. it failed
column4: with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

column1: the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move
column2: egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution
column3: prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

column1: a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a ""high level"" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.
according to court documents made public on friday
column2: a member of trump's presidential transition team
column3: later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner
column4: told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments
column6: to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

column1: flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day

column1: 92194;instagram;2019-01-03 05:52:25;FALSE;"wednesdays are for w o m e nâœ¨
meet stephanie. she was told to try pelvic floor physical therapy for dyspareunia (pain with sex) that she had been experiencing for several years. during her initial evaluation
column2: she appeared to be experiencing symptoms more consistent with vaginismus (inability to tolerate vaginal penetrationâ€”including an internal pelvic examination) due to a history of sexual trauma and assault.

column1: our brains are very talented. they have the ability to bury the memory of traumatic events so far away from consciousness that we almost forget they happened. our *nervous system*â€”the network of nerves that transmit signals between all parts of the bodyâ€”isnâ€™t so forgiving. even the slightest trigger can bring back those memories and send us into a state of mental
we carry stress in different places within the physical body
column5: & (you guessed it) the pelvic floor. when something reminds us of a previous trauma (no matter how far removed)
column6: our brains perceive this as a threat which triggers a physical response (read: fight or flight) or â€œmuscle guarding.â€ over time
column7: our nervous system can become accustomed to this state of up-regulation making it difficult for muscles to â€œrelax
column8: â€ thus perpetuating a cycle of hyper-vigilance

column1: ğŸ—£women: you donâ€™t have to tolerate painful sex.
pelvic pt can help break this cycle. everyone processes trauma differently
column2: so seeing a mental health provider is important
column3: but pt can help you understand the physical manifestation of trauma (aka pain science) and reduce pelvic floor tension.

column1: 92281;instagram;2019-01-03 03:59:34;FALSE;"psychologist dr christine blasey ford delivered one of the most powerful testimonies in the #metoo era when she accused supreme court justice brett kavanaugh of sexual assault. she was made to relive a moment that she said ""drastically altered"" her life
column2: when delivering her testimony in front of a senate judiciary committee consisting of 17 male and four female senators. ford accused kavanaugh of trying to rape her at a high school party some 30 years ago. kavanaugh
column4: forcefully denied the allegation. he was ultimately confirmed in a 50 to 48 vote
column5: with republicans supporting donald trump's pick despite extensive opposition. his nomination inflamed a deep cultural divide in todayâ€™s era of reckoning on sexual assault and harassment. ford and her family became the target of death threats
column6: prompting the launch of a gofundme page to cover their $150
column7: 000 security costs. she recently shut down the page after raising nearly $650

column2: iâ€™m a jewelry/sculpture student going into my senior year this spring. for my thesis project i am exploring themes of protection and defense
column3: especially as they relate to victims of violence. for my thesis collection
column4: i plan to have 3 custom wearable pieces tailored to 3 individuals. the first slot is taken by the person that sparked this idea; someone very close to me suffered from physical harassment
column5: and her piece is going to be a sharp-toothed mask that protects the lower half of her face.

column1: i am seeking two more individuals with whom to collaborate on creating symbolic pieces of body armor-like pieces out of metal. ideally
column2: said individuals should be comfortable sharing their stories with me and have their names and stories and image used in my project. i understand that talking about such a sensitive topic can be difficult and trigger negative emotions
column3: but i hope that i can make the process of talking through your narrative soothing and restorative and hopefully empower you on your life journey. also
column4: i would like to make it clear that the pieces created for this collection are intended to raise awareness about the state of today's society. i do not intend to make money from these 3 specific individual pieces
column5: so they will be one of a kind and will not be reproduced for sale. if you really like what i make as your symbolic item and would like to keep it
column6: we can arrange some sort of barter but the last thing i want is to capitalize on your pain. if the pieces happen to sell
column7: the profits will go to a charity of your choice.

column5: and other presentations that this project may require.

column1: 92347;instagram;2019-01-03 01:45:58;FALSE;i have a political opinion. i only share it on things that affect me deeply. i dont have 2Â¢ on everything that's going on. if im not well educated on something or it hasn't affected me personally for me to have experience with i don't talk about it. so if i share how i feel about something that's my opinion. my opinion does not have to be your opinion nor does it have to represent you if you're close to me. it's my opinion and mine alone. it's my image not anyone else's. i have a strong opinion on things that hurt me and those i love. violence against women has affected me on a level that has only been felt by survivors. our current president and republican party i have strong opinions about considering the security of my existence as an lgbt person and many i know. also i welcome others opinions and understandings
column2: but if you think its wrong of me to have a problem with people who don't respect my existence then who are you!? i don't need respect
column3: i however will not tolerate my rights being taken or people who support that. and mental health
column4: my family is plagued by depression and has a severe suicide rate due to clustering. in 2 years i've lost 3 cousins. i myself struggle with depression and have gone to very dark places. but im getting help. all around im a great girl and person. however
column5: talking about things that truly bother me
column7: and hurt those i know does not make me rude
column14: or selfish. i choose to speak on things that we all should feel strongly about. if you're embarrassed because of my experiences. the problem is not within me

column1: i'm not big into writing poems. i'm also not big into sharing this part of my history. but here's a poem i wrote (and badly edited) about that.
after 7 years my body will be a new one
i guess that means that she is dead
she left me with some memoriesÂ
and she took some to the grave
i donâ€™t want them any more but
i wish i could take his hands from her cold
itâ€™s always sad seeing childrenâ€™s graves
at least some of them died peacefully
never experiencing the horrors of whatÂ
i donâ€™t know what to do with them
iâ€™d make a scrapbook but i donâ€™t think anyone wouldÂ
itâ€™s not the same as showing a new loverÂ
isnâ€™t my life cut up enough anyway?
sticking the pieces onto pages will never change
the fact that the good ones are all missing
i was given the ones i was
i would kill to remember 	the sun 	and strawberries 	and summer
like in that photo of her
but instead i am left with remnants of him
this body is no longer hersÂ
every time i flinch at the touch of my neck
or my senses are sparked by a lover
she never had a proper funeral
i want to be remembered when i die
only a handful know 	she ever existed
and i hold her ghost memories

92446;instagram;2019-01-03 00:02:44;FALSE;lets talk self- injury awareness: when i was a teenager i used to self harm. you can not see it on this picture but my body is filled with scars
column3: ancles and thighs. seemingly picture perfect right? dealing with the aftermaths of abuse
column4: many can turn to self- destructuve behaviour
column5: and there is a lot of stigma bound to that. now i don't self injure
column6: luckily i got help at a young age
column7: but i want people who does not have these issues to understand how serious it is. i want to put emphasis and stress that it is so important to take the time to ask if someone is ok. it can make all the difference in the world. there is a lot of stigma in regards to selfharming
column8: and also you need to understand that selfharming can be so incredibly addictive. it took me years to quit and find new coping mechanisms. this might sound weird
column9: but it was this simple sentence that helped taking the biggest steps towards moving on. it went something like this. ""if i can spend so much energy on being selfdestructive
column10: imagine how much great things i can create if i go for the other extreme"" my anger
column11: and sense of shame turned into pride
column12: my anger a reason to create more beauty and i took pride in that. you are a piece of art know that. you are a warrior. you are worthy of love. i carry my scars with pride
column13: it shows me where i come from
column14: and i would not trade my past for anything
column15: it made me who i am today.if you know someone who self-harms

column1: in previous posts i talked about what shea butter is and also talked about refined vs unrefined shea butter (pls refer to previous posts if you haven't seen them) .
now i wanna talk about the benefits of shea butter to our hair. .
raw shea butter provides moisture and suppleness to dry and damanged hair
it repairs natural hair breakage and itchy skin
shea butter is able to smooth and soften afro hair strands
it helps in combating scalp issues: e.g. drandruff
raw shea butter is a great protection against weather damage (harmattan/winter)
it acts like a shield to protect your hair and skin against sunlight (natural sunscreen) .
this butter can also protect your hair from heat damage

column2: and so you did... some things you let go in order to live.""
i was preyed on by a man who saw that i was vulnerable and thought that he could take advantage.

column1: we met for drinks and a tarot reading. he was also fresh out of a relationship and i thought we could be friends and support one another.
he was so good at making me feel comfortable that i didn't see all of the glaring red flags
column2: i poured my guts out to him about my past abuse and how it made me demisexual. he lied and said he was too. ""through rose colored glasses
column3: all the red flags just look like flags.""

column1: when i was upset one day
column2: he offered to come over and hang out. he wrapped me up in a hug and told me i was gonna be okay. i believed him and i relaxed. we made plans to see a movie later the next week. i felt better.

column1: he came over before the movie and sat on the couch with me. it was nice to just sit next to someone and not feel pressured to do anything.
our first kiss wasn't even on the mouth
column2: he kissed my neck and felt me up before he even got close to my lips.

column1: i was taken aback. this cute guy that i thought cared about me was kissing me. i thought maybe this was something good and true.
but when he made that move
column2: i told him again that i was demisexual. he did it over and over again and told me it wasn't like that...but he wouldn't leave me alone.

column1: but when he gave me an ultimatum that i had to give him what i want or he would leave
column2: i caved. i felt pressured and hurt. my fear of abandonment won and i gave in
column3: trying to ignore the alcohol on his breath. i told myself i was imagining things.

column1: and then he got distracted and distant. contacted me and flattered me just enough to keep me on the hook.
he made up some excuse about wanting to see me again only to tell me he wanted to end it. that my being mentally i'll and disabled just wasn't doable for him.

column2: i should have told him to gtfo. why didn't i? how could i have been so stupid?

column1: but i have to let it all go somehow. i don't want to be haunted anymore. i don't want to be so afraid of trusting others with my heart.

column1: 92819;instagram;2019-01-02 16:57:12;FALSE;"it's a new goddamn year and i am going to clear the air. i need to put it all in black and white.
in 2018 i was sexually harassed at my workplace and put through the humiliating experience of investigation only to have nothing happen.

column3: i got bullied by hr and my coworkers until i quit. hr actually called me and told me that they didn't appreciate that i was talking about ""the incident"" with the coworker who sexualized and groped me and kept his job
column4: despite the fact that i was his supervisor and an all around better employee. ""we made all of these accommodations for you."" i felt the last remaining shred of sanity i had remaining snap. i laughed. ""what accommodations? you sent me in to horrible panic attacks
column6: you let the guy keep his job
column7: and you are now calling me and telling me that i can't talk about it?"" ""just because you don't see them doesn't mean they aren't there."" i hung up and quit my job shortly after. i couldn't take it anymore. not when my coworkers were whispering about me behind my back even though the other girls had the same complaints and wouldn't come forward.

column1: but why would they if your hr's response to your report is to ask you what you did to prevent it.

column2: going to work in a damn wheelchair after being hospitalized for not being able to walk. picking up hours that no one else wanted to work. taking on innumerable responsibilities when we didn't have a manager or when there was an active gunman scare at the mall... i loved my job and i thought i could trust the people there. i thought we were family. but you see how quickly that fell apart when shit hit the fan.

column1: so this is it. i send it out in to the void and i will let the spirits do what they will. i work until it no longer has an effect on me
column2: until i no longer feel ill at the mention of it. i will be free.

column1: 92943;instagram;2019-01-02 14:52:21;FALSE;"kicking off the new year with this gem of a book! i bought it at the airport yesterday on my way home from berlin and have hardly been able to put it down. in this book is the voices of many different women with each their view of and experience with feminism. some of these people you already know - like emma watson and kat denning - others you will want to know after reading their stories! like the women of this book
column2: i have myself experienced sexism and degradation because of my gender - i have even sat in a policeman's office after a sexual attack while he told me
column3: that if it wasn't for the fact that 3 more women before me had reported the same kind of attack he wouldn't have taken me seriously! we experience and we fight gender inequality every single day - whether it is big or small
column4: we all experience it in some way. this book is to me an awakening that i am not alone. others face the same things as me
column5: and if we band together and stand up for our rights we will be strong enough to end the inequality. men and women are not the same. but we are equal!

column1: 92968;instagram;2019-01-02 13:32:26;FALSE;day 2 of 2019 - i tossed and turned all night drifting off to sleep for an hour or two at a time. i know i need to have a productive day and take care of myself today but the anxiety i have has got the best of me. i now lay here away early in the morning and it is almost like being paralyzed. my heart fills like it is beating a mile a minute and my thoughts are sort of all over the place. i start to cry for a couple minutes and then donâ€™t even have the energy to do that. i know i need to get out of bed
column3: drink water and start my day. the thought of all of this is unbearable today. where is the source of my anxiety coming from? i have had a generalized anxiety disorder all my life. for the most part i have been able to function and keep it at bay. years of therapy (forced when i was younger and by choice as an adult) i am not going to therapy these days  because i cannot really afford to pay for it. one of my sources of anxiety. so much debt
column4: so many bills it is like a black hole #yesterdayspic ... my mortgage is due today and when i pay it i will have less than $1000 to my name. what about all the bills that will come my way in the next few days?! my biggest anxiety for today - how would you feel if your boyfriend left the house last night with a packed bag and said he was going out with a friend and he would be back later. you know heâ€™s not coming back later because after more than 10 years you know his habits and the way he is. he then picks a fight and says he is not going to come back since you are now bothering him and if you say another word he will disappear for even longer. he leaves the house doesnâ€™t call or text to say anything else and then turns off his phone for the day. it is mean and cruel what he does and any normal person would be able to get up and walk away. in my head i know what is right and wrong but i donâ€™t know how to do anything else but stay. the thought of leaving or him leaving permanently is much too upsetting for me. #anxiousday #anxiety #selfcare #narcissist #metoo;;en;#yesterdayspic
